author: Niket Nayak
comment_text: Because name â€˜New Xyloâ€™ wouldn't work either...  The new strategy of Mahindra which is lanching 'Facelifts' under name of 'New Cars' is just not enough. Cutting it short and simple: 1) No AT in whole range. 2) Looks like a Van and not an MPV (New Ertiga looks even better) 3) Cramped third row, just a namesake 4) Better options at this price point, definitely HEXA 5) A 7 Seater which is Front wheel drive, Really? 6) Again a 7 Seater with Fuel tank of 45L? (Smaller SUVs like Ecosport has 52L FT Capacity, well that's a Ford BTW) 7) Insulting cargo volume of 190L (New Etriga has 209L with decent 3rd Row Space) 8) Auto Headlamps+ Auto Wipers not available which are available in other CSUVs in this price range Like Brezza and EcoSport 9) No Sunroof even after one spends Rs. 14.4 lakh, Really ? 10) 121 BHP for a 1650 Kgs car is not a good power to weight ratio. (Again Ecosport has 123PS in petrol and 200PS in Diesel, something that actually 'live young' gen drivers would want) 11) Basic features like Gear shift indicator, Cooled Glove box, Auto AC, Key less smart entry, Push button start and stop which makes it very basic as in most MUV Taxi owners don't prefer such features. 12) No Cruise Control, People really buy bigger cars for longer drives (Or else this car was designed for Fleet only?)  at last a small yet significant one, even 'Shark inspired' car doesn't come with shark fin antenna, learn from at least Amaze.

My car later met with an accident and when I went to sell the same, I was getting offer like 50k  for 25 lac car. I finally  sold it for 80K. Mahindra in my view is a basically a Jeep manufacturer who are playing in that zone with refurbished versions of the Logan fitted with an SUV looking body.  I have heard Mahindra SUV is good, though. author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months - :  Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times..  Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months.  list of problems -   1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;   2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;   3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;   4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far  5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far  6.  Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved  7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems  8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick  9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight  Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"

author: Niket Nayak
comment_text: Because name â€˜New Xyloâ€™ wouldn't work either... The new strategy of Mahindra which is lanching 'Facelifts' under name of 'New Cars' is just not enough. Cutting it short and simple: 1) No AT in whole range. 2) Looks like a Van and not an MPV (New Ertiga looks even better) 3) Cramped third row, just a namesake 4) Better options at this price point, definitely HEXA 5) A 7 Seater which is Front wheel drive, Really? 6) Again a 7 Seater with Fuel tank of 45L? (Smaller SUVs like Ecosport has 52L FT Capacity, well that's a Ford BTW) 7) Insulting cargo volume of 190L (New Etriga has 209L with decent 3rd Row Space) 8) Auto Headlamps+ Auto Wipers not available which are available in other CSUVs in this price range Like Brezza and EcoSport 9) No Sunroof even after one spends Rs. 14.4 lakh, Really ? 10) 121 BHP for a 1650 Kgs car is not a good power to weight ratio. (Again Ecosport has 123PS in petrol and 200PS in Diesel, something that actually 'live young' gen drivers would want) 11) Basic features like Gear shift indicator, Cooled Glove box, Auto AC, Key less smart entry, Push button start and stop which makes it very basic as in most MUV Taxi owners don't prefer such features. 12) No Cruise Control, People really buy bigger cars for longer drives (Or else this car was designed for Fleet only?) at last a small yet significant one, even 'Shark inspired' car doesn't come with shark fin antenna, learn from at least Amaze.

comment_text: I used to own a Mahindra SUV called - Rexton. Bought it for 25 Lacs. The after sales for premium customers was also so bad that I decided never to own Mahindra product ( except may be the thar). My car later met with an accident and when I went to sell the same, I was getting offer like 50k for 25 lac car. I finally sold it for 80K. Mahindra in my view is a basically a Jeep manufacturer who are playing in that zone with refurbished versions of the Logan fitted with an SUV looking body. I have heard Mahindra SUV is good, though. And scorpio was good too. But if you are expecting a Car like product - smooth ride quality and good customer service then never buy a Mahindra. If you want to just own a big Vehicle - Thar is good !

author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months - : Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times.. Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months. list of problems -  1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;  2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;  3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;  4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far 5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far 6. Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved 7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems 8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick 9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"

author: prasad kamat
comment_text: Being the owner of xuv 500 i say that this car is fun to drive with excellent fuel economy and also here is list of problems that i have faced till now :- 1. Wheel alignment is never perfect and there is always pull towards left side coz no caster camber setting available in suspension setup.hence once i have to replace shocks to solve the problem . 2. Gearbox bearing manufacturing defect that i found coz of continuous humming noise from left side of engine . Advisor was not agreeing with it but later with lot of effort they found it and replaced under warranty . 3. 3 times front wiper linkage set replaced as it was getting jammed all of sudden that shows the quality of the part. 4.lot of Rusting whether you park ur car under roof or in open (within 2 yrs) . My 4 yr old grand i10 outer body is in crisp condition till now. 5. Headlights  cracking from inside due to heat produced from oem bulbs ( not tempered at all ), high beam alignment was lost coz some plactic part inside it was broken . ( not coveed under warranty) 6. Orvm noisy coz water entering in it 7. Cd was stuck inside system coz i did not use it for 1 month . 8. Clutch slave cylinder failed all of sudden while doing long journey, ( trendy wheels mahindra, kolhapur helped out and repair work was done within 3 hrs ) Despite of soft driving style clutch was 70% worn out and would last for more 10k (total odo 59k km) so i choose to replace it costing total for rs 18k . 9. Rear wiper motor failed once 10. Suspension bushing replaced 3 times or maybe more than that .. i dont remember exactlyğŸ˜‚ every year 11. Black plastic fittings on outer body faded There are many more . But i have to say that service by mahindra for parts replacement under warranty is fabulous. Also emergency service for sudden brakedown that i faced while long journey is excellent as i faced it twice . Hope this information will help you guys

author: Niket Nayak
comment_text: Because name â€˜New Xyloâ€™ wouldn't work either... The new strategy of Mahindra which is lanching 'Facelifts' under name of 'New Cars' is just not enough. Cutting it short and simple: 1) No AT in whole range. 2) Looks like a Van and not an MPV (New Ertiga looks even better) 3) Cramped third row, just a namesake 4) Better options at this price point, definitely HEXA 5) A 7 Seater which is Front wheel drive, Really? 6) Again a 7 Seater with Fuel tank of 45L? (Smaller SUVs like Ecosport has 52L FT Capacity, well that's a Ford BTW) 7) Insulting cargo volume of 190L (New Etriga has 209L with decent 3rd Row Space) 8) Auto Headlamps+ Auto Wipers not available which are available in other CSUVs in this price range Like Brezza and EcoSport 9) No Sunroof even after one spends Rs. 14.4 lakh, Really ? 10) 121 BHP for a 1650 Kgs car is not a good power to weight ratio. (Again Ecosport has 123PS in petrol and 200PS in Diesel, something that actually 'live young' gen drivers would want) 11) Basic features like Gear shift indicator, Cooled Glove box, Auto AC, Key less smart entry, Push button start and stop which makes it very basic as in most MUV Taxi owners don't prefer such features. 12) No Cruise Control, People really buy bigger cars for longer drives (Or else this car was designed for Fleet only?) at last a small yet significant one, even 'Shark inspired' car doesn't come with shark fin antenna, learn from at least Amaze.

My car later met with an accident and when I went to sell the same, I was getting offer like 50k for 25 lac car. I finally sold it for 80K. Mahindra in my view is a basically a Jeep manufacturer who are playing in that zone with refurbished versions of the Logan fitted with an SUV looking body. I have heard Mahindra SUV is good, though. And scorpio was good too. But if you are expecting a Car like product - smooth ride quality and good customer service then never buy a Mahindra. author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months - : Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times.. Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months. list of problems -  1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;  2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;  3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;  4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far 5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far 6. Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved 7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems 8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick 9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"

author: prasad kamat
comment_text: Being the owner of xuv 500 i say that this car is fun to drive with excellent fuel economy and also here is list of problems that i have faced till now :- 1. Wheel alignment is never perfect and there is always pull towards left side coz no caster camber setting available in suspension setup.hence once i have to replace shocks to solve the problem . 2. Gearbox bearing manufacturing defect that i found coz of continuous humming noise from left side of engine . Advisor was not agreeing with it but later with lot of effort they found it and replaced under warranty . 3. 3 times front wiper linkage set replaced as it was getting jammed all of sudden that shows the quality of the part. 4.lot of Rusting whether you park ur car under roof or in open (within 2 yrs) . My 4 yr old grand i10 outer body is in crisp condition till now. 5. Headlights  cracking from inside due to heat produced from oem bulbs ( not tempered at all ), high beam alignment was lost coz some plactic part inside it was broken . ( not coveed under warranty) 6. Orvm noisy coz water entering in it 7. Cd was stuck inside system coz i did not use it for 1 month . 8. Clutch slave cylinder failed all of sudden while doing long journey, ( trendy wheels mahindra, kolhapur helped out and repair work was done within 3 hrs ) Despite of soft driving style clutch was 70% worn out and would last for more 10k (total odo 59k km) so i choose to replace it costing total for rs 18k . 9. Rear wiper motor failed once 10. Suspension bushing replaced 3 times or maybe more than that .. i dont remember exactlyğŸ˜‚ every year 11. Black plastic fittings on outer body faded There are many more . But i have to say that service by mahindra for parts replacement under warranty is fabulous. Also emergency service for sudden brakedown that i faced while long journey is excellent as i faced it twice . Hope this information will help you guys

author: Niket Nayak
comment_text: Because name â€˜New Xyloâ€™ wouldn't work either... The new strategy of Mahindra which is lanching 'Facelifts' under name of 'New Cars' is just not enough. Cutting it short and simple: 1) No AT in whole range. 2) Looks like a Van and not an MPV (New Ertiga looks even better) 3) Cramped third row, just a namesake 4) Better options at this price point, definitely HEXA 5) A 7 Seater which is Front wheel drive, Really? 6) Again a 7 Seater with Fuel tank of 45L? (Smaller SUVs like Ecosport has 52L FT Capacity, well that's a Ford BTW) 7) Insulting cargo volume of 190L (New Etriga has 209L with decent 3rd Row Space) 8) Auto Headlamps+ Auto Wipers not available which are available in other CSUVs in this price range Like Brezza and EcoSport 9) No Sunroof even after one spends Rs. 14.4 lakh, Really ? 10) 121 BHP for a 1650 Kgs car is not a good power to weight ratio. (Again Ecosport has 123PS in petrol and 200PS in Diesel, something that actually 'live young' gen drivers would want) 11) Basic features like Gear shift indicator, Cooled Glove box, Auto AC, Key less smart entry, Push button start and stop which makes it very basic as in most MUV Taxi owners don't prefer such features. 12) No Cruise Control, People really buy bigger cars for longer drives (Or else this car was designed for Fleet only?) at last a small yet significant one, even 'Shark inspired' car doesn't come with shark fin antenna, learn from at least Amaze.

My car later met with an accident and when I went to sell the same, I was getting offer like 50k for 25 lac car. I finally sold it for 80K. Mahindra in my view is a basically a Jeep manufacturer who are playing in that zone with refurbished versions of the Logan fitted with an SUV looking body. I have heard Mahindra SUV is good, though. author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months - : Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times.. Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months. list of problems -  1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;  2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;  3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;  4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far 5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far 6. Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved 7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems 8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick 9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"

author: prasad kamat
comment_text: Being the owner of xuv 500 i say that this car is fun to drive with excellent fuel economy and also here is list of problems that i have faced till now :- 1. Wheel alignment is never perfect and there is always pull towards left side coz no caster camber setting available in suspension setup.hence once i have to replace shocks to solve the problem . 2. Gearbox bearing manufacturing defect that i found coz of continuous humming noise from left side of engine . Advisor was not agreeing with it but later with lot of effort they found it and replaced under warranty . 3. 3 times front wiper linkage set replaced as it was getting jammed all of sudden that shows the quality of the part. 4.lot of Rusting whether you park ur car under roof or in open (within 2 yrs) . My 4 yr old grand i10 outer body is in crisp condition till now. 5. Headlights  cracking from inside due to heat produced from oem bulbs ( not tempered at all ), high beam alignment was lost coz some plactic part inside it was broken . ( not coveed under warranty) 6. Orvm noisy coz water entering in it 7. Cd was stuck inside system coz i did not use it for 1 month . 8. Clutch slave cylinder failed all of sudden while doing long journey, ( trendy wheels mahindra, kolhapur helped out and repair work was done within 3 hrs ) Despite of soft driving style clutch was 70% worn out and would last for more 10k (total odo 59k km) so i choose to replace it costing total for rs 18k . 9. Rear wiper motor failed once 10. Suspension bushing replaced 3 times or maybe more than that .. i dont remember exactlyğŸ˜‚ every year 11. Black plastic fittings on outer body faded There are many more . But i have to say that service by mahindra for parts replacement under warranty is fabulous. Also emergency service for sudden brakedown that i faced while long journey is excellent as i faced it twice . Hope this information will help you guys

author: Rao Sahab
comment_text: ok, so I am a big critic of this but let me tell you something really interesting. I hate when they want to put everything in this and try to travel 200 miles. I have always been suggesting its a farm machine and in USA its rightly set as so. It can be street legal but not a hwy vehicle by long shot. They are making the next generation and by the works its quite interesting and a bit bigger. That said, I have seen the engine work on many models here and it will just keep going on and on, there is hardly a diesel, even your fiats and fords fail, toyotas collapse, where a mahindra can go.. I prefer TATA, who build fiat engines for India as fiat can never do the numbers alone. But i would admint the mahindras make excellent engines and strong bodies.The engine and the heavy steel is worth what you pay for. It is something that you can keep for a long time if you just make sure you add anti rust coatings and exhaust treatments once every few years. Apparently you will put it in mud, so best treated against rust. I do that to all my cars, even the ones that dont face the rains.

comment_text: I would love to have the cash to drop on a dual cab Landcruiser however it is way over my budget. I bought a brand new Mahindra Pik Up dual cab with alloy tray and steel winch compatible bullbar instead and after 20,000 km's I am still smiling. No issues, cheap on fuel and great offroad (Eatons Mechanical Auto Locker in the rear as standard). They are down on power compared to any other modern big name 4wd however it still keeps up with traffic and will sit on any speed limit in Australia with no worries. Basically it comes down to money. If I could afford $70k + for a vehicle, I would own a Dual Cab Landcruiser, but I could buy 2.5 of the Mahindra Pik Up (with Alloy Tray and Bullbar already fitted) for the same price as an optioned but still stock 79 Series. Only time will tell about reliability in the long run but I was willing to take the gamble and so far its been great :-)

comment_text: "The way my Deere 3320 was designed for the BH was brilliant. It used the rock shaft arms to lift the BH up and you lowered it and it locked into channels then you put two pins in the top. I paid 29K out the door for a 3320 with 41.50 tires, the big back hoe (448), a 60"" 7 Iron mid mount mower and a 300CX Front End Loader. Looks like a similarly equipeed Mahindra (MSRP) is $38,233 for the 1533 Shuttle with the MMM and the BH/FEL. They look like nice machines but I'm not seeing a major cost savings. If I ever had issues with my 3320 the dealer sent a roll back to my house and picked it up free of charge and took it in for the warranty work. I really had no issues other than the rock shaft arms needed adjusted up two splines to lift the back hoe higher."

comment_text: "I've been looking at this size tractor and none are made in America, some are assembled here.Â  ""Assembled"" can range from putting tires on to putting the components together.Â  Deere's 30 series is made in Asia.Â  Mahindra's 15 and 25 seriesÂ is assembled here from Indian or Korean components.Â  New Holland and Case IH tractors this size are LS tractors made in South Korea.Â  Kubota is pretty much assembled here, but the parts come from Japan.Â  Kiotis are made in Korea.Â  Yanmars are made somewhere in Asia, they also have made compacts for John Deere.Â  That exhausts the makes with dealers anywhere within 150 miles of me.For what it's worth the Mahindra and LS tractors look like the best bang for the buck, short of the Chinese tractors Northern Tool sells from their catalog.Â  I really don't want to go there."

author: sideskraft
comment_text: "Deere now lags behind other compacts in performance, quality and robustness. Deere's marketing budget is probably more than the revenues of most of their competitors, and in today's media saturated culture, that has a major impact on sales. Remember when Honda, Toyota and Datsun (now Nissan) hit the USA like a tidal wave in the 70s, and by the 90s they had captured significant market share -- today they have some of the best selling vehicles. Then Hyundai and KIA came to the fray and have carved out a major slice of the market pie. I see companies like Mahindra, LS, TYM, Branson and Kioti slowly chipping away at the Deere and Kubota monopoly, with more quality products and increasing numbers of dealers. The internet forums have exposed the shortcomings of the Deere product and the features and advantages of their competitors, and tens of millions of Deere marketing dollars can't change that. Were it not for the internet, these smaller companies wouldn't have a chance. I see Deere being forced to up their game to improve their product, or risk further market share declines. If nothing else, the ""little guys"" have brought better machines to our market, giving us consumers more choices and more bang for the buck. Very few used ""off brand"" tractors are for sale, which I believe is because their owners are so happy with them -- the ones I have seen for sale are priced surprisingly high (and two I wanted to see were sold within days of being advertised). This tells me buyers are becoming educated. I haven't yet decided what brand my first tractor will be, but unless there are significant up-front cost savings, it's unlikely it will be green."

author: eddiejenn12
comment_text: "I love John Deere; I have owned several medium sized (50 or so HP) and a few smaller ones and they have been good machines. But I had a John Deere 5300 (55ish HP) and a Mahindra 4525 (46ish) at the same time and the Mahindra runs circles around the JD. The 5300 might have just been a bad model but the transmission was sloppy and the 4525 has a basic traditional transmission that just works. As far as power I cant tell a difference in PTO power, but I can tell you side by side the 4525s front end loader seems to lift more weight easier and when I put the bucket on the ground the 4525 can ""push"" larger dirt piles without loosing traction. I also lilked how the Mahindra was all metal, vs my JD had plastic hood and fenders. Again I owned both and I got rid of the John Deere. I agree with other peoples post about resale value being higher with JD but I am not planning on selling my tractor. I just wanted simple and powerful. I would never turn a JD down, but side by side I would go with Mahindra again (and save money)."

author: Palmetto NDN
comment_text: Locking differential is where it's at. ANY real serious off road vehicle has locking diff. All the torque, power distribution, and limited slip technologies in the world won't help you if the working wheel has no traction under it. One time I was coming down a mountain in a friend's Suzuki Jimny we stopped moving at a flat plane because we were in a rut and the wheel getting all the power had no ground under it. We got out of it bul sliding a big rock under the wheel and me standing on the bumper to force the wheel down onto the rock down, moving .3m at a time until we got out. No locking diff = just a trail truck.

author: SP Singh
comment_text: Took a test drive of Petrol XUV300 1) Drives ok not much noise 2) Gear shift is lousy...to much play (try Honda WRV or ecosport or even brezza) 3) Gear Shifter vibration even in petrol version.... Unacceptable 4) Driver footwell area is very congested....every gear change was obstructed by the central console while moving the foot too or away from clutch...almost no space between console and clutch ...very uncomfortable to change gears ...would get worse in traffic. 5) Who needs a heated ORVM ? 8 out of 12 months AC is in use in most parts of the country. 6) Pathetic quality of rear plate lights ? 7) Rear seat - centre - misses out on 3 point seat belt, Why ? Not a luxury but necessity 8) Basic model misses out on driver seat height adjustment ? When will these manufactures understand that drivers come in all sizes and all of them require seat adjustment, its not a luxury, but necessity. 9) Basic Model - is a shame for this class and price. 10) Maintenance cost indicated was 26 paise /KM , that Rs 2600 for every service on 10000 KM. Not entirely sure what all that would cover specially in latter services, considering that all 4 disc pads would need replacement around 30-40K.

author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months - : Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times.. Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months. list of problems -  1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;  2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;  3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;  4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far 5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far 6. Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved 7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems 8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick 9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight 10. Car windshield cracked unexpectedly, was changed by the dealer! Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"

comment_text: I would never wish anyone to have to fix anything at all. But it can't be avoided no matter what color it is. What I have learned is that on so many topics, people are very passionate about their point of view. The reality is, the more heated a debate becomes over any topic you can think of, the less difference it makes at the end of the day. That sounds silly, but it's the naked truth. People become prideful of the choices they make, right or wrong. Which is better, Chevy, Ford, Dodge, Toyota, Nissan, etc. . . . ? And they justify their choices all kinds of ways, such that logic departed a long long time ago. Bottom line: nothing is perfect. if you have a Mahindra, Kubota, or John Deere, none of them are so bad that you should feel compelled to buy something different. Again, sorry for what might be an early replacement for fuel lines and electrical problems. But it problem will be something different for Kubota, Deere, Kioti, etc. A lot can be said for having the devil you know, rather than the devil you don't. Come on people! author: Balasubramanian V
comment_text: I would prefer the Ford Ecosport anyday. Strength and stability with reasonable off roading capability. The Ecosport has proved itself. Ford is also known to provide good service though a tad expensive. As value for money, I would pick the Brezza which has done quite well so far as safety is concerned, is overall a good package, even though we have the herd mentality clamouring about cheap plastics and what not. The Brezza is presently the King of this segment. While presently the XUV 300 is selling in large numbers, one has to do a wait and watch situation to see how it goes in future. Even in Chennai, where good service is the norm for all car companies, Mahindra' service is not what it ought to be. The Nexon is overall a good package but the horrendous Tata after sales service makes it deal breaker, though fortunately we are yet to witness the donning of body armours prior to a visit. Tata's perceived policy of virtually abandoning its customers to incompent and unscrupulous dealers and the fact that Tata Motors is in a financial hole does not inspire confidence.

author: obsolete professor
comment_text: "The new Massy tractors have a satellite uplink. Upon start, a contact sends a signal up which first goes through the bank to see if your payments are current while simultaneously locating the tractor via GPS. (notice I didn't say ""your tractor""). If ok, it then gets relayed to the air quality board to see if your intended plow area is predicted to have a dusty day. If that's good, the start request gets forwarded to the IRS to see if your farm fuel tax exemption is correct. There are a few more links it has to make before the signal comes back down and enables the start. Or....the red (how appropriate) solenoid under the seat can be bypassed with a jumper wire. Be sure to wrap the tractor in tin foil."

comment_text: To the gentleman in the video, If your tractor is like the 4025 I owned, or the 5570 I currently own, I can see your problem at the 0:13 mark as to why your tractor wonâ€™t start, pretty well. Unless yours is different (and it may be), your PTO lever is pushed forward, which makes the PTO engage. Your tractor has a safety that will not allow the engine to start with the PTO engaged. I never saw you disengage the lever. You absolutely bypassed the PTO safety switch when you straight wired the switch, so it will now start with the PTO engaged or disengaged, or in 8th gear, for what that matters. Iâ€™ll not disagree Mahindras have known wiring issues, but Iâ€™ve not seen any Mahindras where the PTO lever was forward for disengage. I think you may have been chasing a phantom problem there.

author: PhillipB78
comment_text: Ok so, I have a couple of things here, after watching this video through from beginning to end. First of all, This day in time, folks, across the board, you can not expect to get the kind of life and trouble free operation out of anything, including tractors/cars/trucks, that we did 30 or 40 years ago. I've got a couple of international tractors from the 60's and 70's, that still run well, despite years of heavy work and abuse. My ol' 574 doesn't look worth a damn anymore, but she'll fire up and run all day long, reliably. That said, Trust me, if you go buy a brand new tractor from almost anyone, you'll end up with these sorts of issues, or worse. I have a neighbor who purchased a new john Deere about 18 months ago, I don't recall the model number, but it's in that 80 to 100 horsepower range, and....it's now sitting in the damned shop, needing about 6 grand worth of work to the electronic transmission....and of course, there's still that predictable fight about who's going to pay for it, dealer, or manufacturer. Now personally, if I'm going to go pay 120 grand for a new tractor, someone damn well better make that right when electronics fail at less than 2 years old, with less than 250 hours on the machine in total. I truly believe that, all in all, for what you spend on them, Mahindra tractors are a worth while investment. Sure, you will probably have electrical grimlins to sort out, and the ocasional stupid crap like fuel lines, and hydraulic cylinder rebuilds, but, I can tell you, I purchased a brand new Mahindra 3510 in 2007, it's 4wd, with both a back hoe and front end loader, and out the door, was right at 21,000 bucks. I bought it as a cheap tractor, to do a specific set of jobs. Sure, I've put it through hell, and yes, I've had the same sorts of small problems mentioned here in this video, but....it's now January of 2019, and all in all, she's still running balls to the walls, and treetop tall....if it blew up tomorrow, which is unlikely since at 5420 hours she still doesn't use an abnormal amount of oil for a diesel, I'd be out looking at another one tomorrow. I've had other small tractors, and there are other decent ones out there, but usually they cost more, and have problems that are far worse than these....I'll fix cheap wiring, if my diesel engine and hydraulic pump system will continue to lift when I overload the damn thing with bricks and rock, time and time again.

author: Bill Gebhart
comment_text: "I went to a Mahindra dealer a few years ago, and looked at several tractors. I had previously owned an 18.5 hp mid-70's Kubota. When I went back to the same dealer a couple of years later and was seriously looking to buy a tractor, the dealer had quit selling Mahindra because when he did warranty work on them, the company was slow to pay him for the work, and always fought him for the money that was due. In some cases he didn't even get paid. By then he was selling LS Tractors. I am SO HAPPY I found a Massey Ferguson dealer 10 miles from my home. In 2012, I ended up buying a 2009 Massey 1533 with a loader, 7 ft blade with only 142 hours on it. The back tires still had the ""new tire nubs"" on them. He had sold it new for $24,500 and the buyer got a divorce and sold the tractor back to the dealer. He sold it to me for $14,500. I am so happy and impressed with it. I love the Shuttle Shift and so glad I have left and right brakes. It has always exceeded my expectations. My ""only"" disappointment is that it came with industrial bar tires like the tractors you see in this video, instead of Ag tires. The bar tires are great in dry weather, on pavement, dirt, shale, etc, but pitiful and almost unusable and dangerous in snow, mud and/or ice. I bought chains for the back tires for winter and steer with the brakes a lot in winter. I talked to the dealer a couple of years ago, and he told me he no longer gets bar tires on new tractors--Only Ag tires."

author: Bill Gebhart
comment_text: "In 2012, I bought a used 2009 Massey Ferguson 1533 with a loader and 8ft woods blade. I bought it from the dealer who had sold it because the owner was going through a divorce and sold it back to the dealer. The tractor only had 142 hours on it and still had the nubs on the tires. The dealer completely serviced it, washed and waxed it. Right now it has 995 hours on it and it has always exceeded my expectations. New, it sold for $24,500, and I bought it for $14, 500. I do everything with it--load lots of shale and dirt, grade and ditch the drive, firewood, pick up logs and load them to take to the saw mill, brush hog, dig out stumps, clear brush, carry hay, tools, etc. The only thing I don't like is that it came with the bar industrial tires; if you're driving on any thing but dirt, shale or gravel, you're going to spin and have limited steering--on ice, snow or mud, those tires are like slicks. I also hate the ""Woods"" blade!!! To date, I've spent another $500 having a machine shop modify and repair it; Yesterday, I saw another broken factory weld.  ""WOODS"" is another way to spell 'JUNK!"" I had looked at Mahindra a couple of years before purchasing my Massey, and when I went back to that same dealer, he was selling ""LS"" tractors. He told me he quit selling Mahindra because the company did not adhere to their warranties, and when they did, payment to him from the company was slow if at all. Anyway. I love my Massey Ferguson. Both of my brothers-in-law own the exact same tractor and are just as happy with their purchase."

author: Gaurav Malik
comment_text: "I am owner of the plush new XUV500 - 3rd iteration and here is my feedback, 11,800 kms and 9 months: Its a gimmick - I doubt the reliability of all these features - and even if so, I think people would like a reliable car over multiple features that may or may not work at times.. Mahindra has just put in lots of features with not the best of materials...dont get drawn into such gimmicks...I regret buying the ""plush new XUV500"" - 11,800 kms, 9 months. list of problems -  1. Middle Seats made horrible noise - changed at 2500 kms;  2. Rear Disk Brakes had massive rust issues - again changed;  3. Sunroof made horrible noise - some lubrication post multiple complaints;  4. Infotainment has been an issue to begin with - went direct ie when i turned the car off the system was still on, radio misses signal every more often than not, Android Auto GPS loses signal every now and then, Android auto does not come on every now and then, bluetooth track does not update every now and then, system is awfully slow sometimes - no solution in sight so far 5. Wipers make horrible noise when cleaning the windshield - no solution in sight so far 6. Auto folding side view mirrors - have a mind of their own, sometimes they work and sometimes they dont; will not take command from inside door panel button as well sometimes - will not fold or unfold if you press the button on the inside driver side door panel - never been solved 7. Bad vibrations from the car and the suspension is not the best, thuds feel very strong inside the car - low quality plastics it seems 8. Start stop function sometimes does not work - gimmick 9. Horn vibration - filters through the speakers and into the music you play - no solution in sight Overall while Mahindra gives all these super duper features - I dont know how reliable they are. This is from a person who owns and drives their 3rd iteration of the XUV500 ie the ""plush new XUV"". The CAR HAS BARELY DONE 12000 Kms in 9 months! Stay Away from Mahindra cars!"
